📘 Task 1 – Learn Linux Permissions

Every file has permissions for:

Owner (u)
Group (g)
Others (o)

Example:

-rwxr-xr--

Breakdown:

-          → File
rwx        → Owner
r-x        → Group
r--        → Others

Permission values:

Symbol	Meaning	Value
r	Read	4
w	Write	2
x	Execute	1

Examples:

Number	Meaning
777	Everyone has full access
755	Owner full, others read & execute
700	Owner only
644	Owner read/write, others read
600	Private file
📘 Task 2 – Practice Commands

Run these commands one by one:

pwd

touch demo.txt

ls -l

chmod 777 demo.txt

ls -l

chmod 755 demo.txt

ls -l

chmod 644 demo.txt

ls -l

chmod 600 demo.txt

ls -l

Observe how permissions change.

📘 Task 3 – Symbolic Permissions
chmod u+x demo.txt

chmod g+w demo.txt

chmod o-r demo.txt

chmod a+x demo.txt

ls -l

Understand:

u = User
g = Group
o = Others
a = All
📘 Task 4 – Ownership

Check file owner:

ls -l

Change owner (requires sudo):

sudo chown $USER demo.txt

Change group:

sudo chgrp $USER demo.txt

View current user:

whoami

View user ID:

id
📘 Task 5 – Create Users (Lab)

Only if you're using your own Linux machine or VM.

sudo adduser devopsuser

sudo passwd devopsuser

sudo usermod -aG sudo devopsuser

groups devopsuser

Delete the user (optional):

sudo deluser devopsuser
📘 Task 6 – Shell Script

Create commands.sh:

#!/bin/bash

echo "Current User:"
whoami

echo ""

echo "User ID:"
id

echo ""

echo "Creating file..."
touch demo.txt

echo ""

echo "Current permissions:"
ls -l demo.txt

echo ""

echo "Changing permissions to 755..."
chmod 755 demo.txt

ls -l demo.txt

echo ""

echo "Changing permissions to 644..."
chmod 644 demo.txt

ls -l demo.txt

echo ""

echo "Adding execute permission..."
chmod +x demo.txt

ls -l demo.txt

Make it executable:

chmod +x commands.sh
./commands.sh
